Question: I am trying to set up a method used by three different buttons. I want to load one of three different views depending on which of them is pressed. To do so, I thought about passing as an argument the button itself. But I was unable, due to javaFX not recognising the method with the new argument.

How can I get the `fx:id` of the caller button so I can make the distinction between each of them? Here's what I got this far. I just need to initialize `pressed` variable so it will do its thing.

```
if (pressed == edgeModify){
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/edgeView.fxml"));
} else if (pressed == sectionModify){
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/sectionView.fxml"));
} else {
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/LayerView.fxml"));
}

```

Answer:

1

The approach you are taking is to pass the button itself as an argument to the `FXMLLoader`. However, JavaFX does not recognise the method when an object is passed in. Instead, it uses the object passed in as the argument to the method. You can get the `fx:id` of the caller button by passing the button itself as an argument to the `FXMLLoader`, and then accessing the `fx:id` of the button passed in.

Thus, to get the `fx:id` of the caller button so you can make the distinction between each of them, you can use the `fx:id` of the passed-in button as the argument to the method.

```
if (pressed == edgeModify) {
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/edgeView.fxml")));
} else if (pressed == sectionModify) {
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/sectionView.fxml")));
} else {
    loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/digitalia/view/LayerView.fxml")));
```

This will return the correct view based on the button that is pressed. The `fx:id` of the passed-in button is used as the argument to the method, and JavaFX uses this argument as the argument to the method.

